	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Quite the contrary I said I didn't understand what you meant meaning I wanted a clarification of your point. I don't have anything against you, you shouldn't take offense to someone with a different opinion than you. And you didn't offend me and I am not angry toward you. And I did give examples in previous posts about the limits of the SNES. 
<br />
<br />Sprite scaling is not possible in hardware or software on the SNES in practice anyway so what you say amount storing multiple sizes of a sprite in ROM would be the only real way to go with that. 
<br />
<br />You say RAM could be used for "other purposes" if graphics are transfered from ROM to VRAM. What other purpose should this RAM be used for? And lots of SNES games already do transfer graphics from ROM to VRAM. The only reason they wouldn't do this is if they use software compression for graphics. 
<br />
<br />While I haven't played Art of Fighting anytime lately I do agree with your statement that without the ROM size limitation and further development time to optimize a port as best they could I'm sure a better port could have been made. 
<br />
<br />Really when it comes to ports of arcade games on superior hardware to the SNES I recommend looking at the best examples of ports that were made such as Mortal Kombat II and Super Street Fighter II. I think you would agree for the SNES these were both very well received ports despite not being close to 1:1 with the arcade original. While the subject of if a perfect or better port is possible is interesting I think it is ultimately futile sense SNK is not interested in producing a new SNES port and I don't believe anyone is interested in reverse engineering a NeoGeo game to then port it to SNES. If they were that would be very cool. 
<br />
<br />naI, I was just making a point about the idea of pushing something to the perceived limit. I would agree that a game with no slowdown is better but how are you to tell by playing a game what is pushing the processor "to the limit". The same can be said about other aspects. It's a strange term to use, pushing a game console to the limit.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
