	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">MottZilla wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The SNES has pretty well defined "limits". When a game on SNES has slowdown, wouldn't that be pushing the processor to the limit because processing each frame is now taking so long that a new frame is not ready in time to maintain 60 frames per second? What about when too many sprites are on the same line and some disappear? Isn't that pushing it to the limit?</div><br />You are mentioning specific hardware limitations that do not dictate the limitations of the whole system. If a game lags because it couldn't finish it's game logic in time, it doesn't necessarily mean that the game is pushing limits, it might just mean that it wasn't programmed as efficiently as it could have been.<br /><br />If the sprites disappear it doesn't mean a game is pushing the system to the limits either. Sure it hit a video hardware limitation, but a programmer that really wanted to get rid of this problem could create a drawing system where objects that don't move (or move less than others) were drawn to the background to make the sprite use less intense. Few people did things like this, because it's easier to have a single object drawing system that always uses sprites.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">How about Super FX or SA-1? Wouldn't that be pushing the limits even further by adding a new CPU?</div><br />As is often said by some people on this board when we discuss NES mappers, having hardware extensions doesn't automatically make a good game. Look at Hard Drivin' on the Genesis/MD, or those C64 games with 3D polygons similar to the ones in Starfox. They worked without enhancements, and looked pretty similar to Starfox, they were just slower. The Starfox programmers decided they needed an extra CPU, which is the exact opposite of pushing a system to it's limits. They decided to stay away from the limits and put the load on a second processor, instead of using creativity to try solving the problem in a different way.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I don't think developers were that lazy</div><br />I wouldn't say lazy, I'd say that they were on tight schedules and couldn't dedicate enough time to make sure each project was as good/efficient/fast as they could be. Also, many times they weren't so experienced with the processors or consoles they had to work with. Some were probably lazy though.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">The things I see as limits to SNES games mainly are CPU processing power and memory which I think can be complaints on any system.</div><br />The thing is that many developers are scared of these particular limitations and will not even consider trying new things, because in business there is no time for this.<br /><br />The advantage hobbyist programmers have is that there is no pressure. There are no deadlines, no boss nagging you about projects. We have all the time in the world to learn about the systems. I for example have been studying the NES for over 9 years. How much time do you think programmers back in the 80's had to study the platforms? We have the potential to do better, much better than was done back then, but most people don't dare, they are too conservative and think that the current game library is the absolute proof of all that can be done and nobody will ever make anything better.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Both can be added and were added to the SNES in various forms.</div>
<br />If you need to turn a console into a Frankenstein in order to make games for it, you'd better move on to something more powerful and be conservative in that new platform.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


