	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">MottZilla wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I would agree that a game with no slowdown is better but how are you to tell by playing a game what is pushing the processor "to the limit".</div><br />You can push a console to it's limits without stressing the CPU. You can make a pretty cool video effect using pre-calculated data from ROM in a way that the CPU is not doing much more than giving a few commands to the video system. If it looks more advanced than what that console can ordinarily output, you could say you're pushing some limits. You don't have to stress every single piece of hardware in the console, just have it do something it wasn't designed to do and you are pushing limits.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">It's a strange term to use, pushing a game console to the limit.</div>
<br />Not really. I'd define this as "using tricks to make a console do something that is trivial on newer, more advanced consoles". Of course you could just go and use the newer console, which is what professional developers usually do (after a brief period of trying to push the older console to it's limits), but for some of us internet nerds the fun is in seeing how far we can go with an specific console.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


