	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The reason I find it strange though is as the "demo scene" was mentioned before as an example to what is technically possible on a system. But there is a difference between what is technically possible and what is practical in a real world setting. I don't doubt that you can do some crazy things that look amazing on many systems but sometimes while whatever is being done is very impressive it's just not practical for real use in a game. 
<br />
<br />About the two points mentioned. What if the game lags but it was absolutely optimized to the maximum potential? Is it then pushing the system to the limit? Who's to say without the actual source code and studying it if it's efficient or not? About sprites disappearing, what if it just wasn't feasible to do what you say and it was just unavoidable? I just find the whole notion of "pushing to the limit" very much opinion based and not directly related to facts. 
<br />
<br />The whole original point being talked about was trying to achieve something well beyond the limits of the SNES which are cold hard facts. There is no trickery to be done to somehow push the SNES beyond it. 
<br />
<br />Personally I don't find fancy technical work to be as important as designing a good and fun game. You don't need a bag full of tricks if you have a solid game. Some of the tricks are quite cool but aren't needed.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


