	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">MottZilla wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">But there is a difference between what is technically possible and what is practical in a real world setting.</div><br />I agree with you. I believe I said something similar recently.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">What if the game lags but it was absolutely optimized to the maximum potential?</div><br />It's hard to state that a piece of code has been optimized to the max. Even if a programmer optimizes an algorithm that performs a particular task to the maximum, who can say there isn't another completely different algorithm that does the same task but more efficiently? The way in which a programmer approaches a problem makes a huge difference, not just how optimally coded the selected solution is. You can code SMB a trillion different ways (which will look exactly the same to a player), the odds of picking the best one are pretty slim.<br /><br />IMO, pushing the limits isn't necessarily using all the resources of a console, but making it look like you are. It's much like magic tricks, it's about what appears to be happening, not what actually is.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">About sprites disappearing, what if it just wasn't feasible to do what you say and it was just unavoidable?</div><br />I proposed one solution (the one I'm using in my sonic game for the NES), there are probably others. The SNES and the MD have enough sprites to cover the whole horizontal area, if they are flickering/disappearing the programmer must have done something wrong.<br /><br />In Sonic 1 (MD) you can see sprites disappearing if you stand on a bridge while invincible. Why the hell did they need all those stars around Sonic? In Sonic 2, the invincibility effect uses way fewer sprites, and it doesn't look any worse. When designing a game, you can make choices that are easier on the hardware, but the trick is not letting the players notice the choices were made because of limitations. If you're having less stars, make them spin really fast in a pseudo-3D path... It will look like that was the intention all along, not that you were trying to save sprites.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I just find the whole notion of "pushing to the limit" very much opinion based and not directly related to facts.</div><br />I agree with you.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">The whole original point being talked about was trying to achieve something well beyond the limits of the SNES which are cold hard facts. There is no trickery to be done to somehow push the SNES beyond it.</div><br />Sure. If the question is "is a 1:1 port possible?", the answer is clearly "no", but if the intention is to make a really good-looking fighting game, my opinion is that it's certainly possible to do something better than Street Fighter of Mortal Kombat.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Personally I don't find fancy technical work to be as important as designing a good and fun game. You don't need a bag full of tricks if you have a solid game. Some of the tricks are quite cool but aren't needed.</div>
<br />Of course gameplay is more important than graphics, but making the graphics look sophisticated is a good part of the fun. That is my opinion as a game developer, others might not care so much about the graphical presentation.

		

		</td>
