	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Wow hot debate going on there. Anyway I'll share a few troughts...
<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">The SNES and the MD have enough sprites to cover the whole horizontal area, if they are flickering/disappearing the programmer must have done something wrong. </div>
<br />You forgot that sprites can override eachother. This happens a lot in SOM, where you can have 3 players, their 3 weapons, 3 enemies, and possibly other graphical effects (such as splashes or damage indicators) on the same scanline... Of couse this don't happen very regularly, but it DOES happen. Compared to all the flickering of Gradius/Lifeforce/Parodius series on the NES it's not much.
<br />
<br />When it comes to SNES demoscenes, there would probably not be very impressive because.... the hardware features HDMA, that many games used extensively. Most C64/NES demoscenes completely take advantage of mid-frame and midscanline register changes, which is not a standard thing on those systems. But on the SNES it can be done all in hardware very easily, the vast majority of games used that so it would really not be impressive.
<br />Now by using a clever combination of HDMA, Mode 7 or by taking advantage of "tile per offset" mode, some brand new awesome effects that haven't been seen yet could probably be done...

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


