	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">magno wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><a href="http://www.elotrolado.net/hilo_podria-una-snes-o-md-con-lo-mejor-de-la-aes_1327719_s350" class="postlink">http://www.elotrolado.net/hilo_podria-una-snes-o-md-con-lo-mejor-de-la-aes_1327719_s350</a></div>
<br />Looking at that page I remembered that there is a cheap (cheap as in not CPU/RAM/ROM intensive) method for scaling sprites that works well if not much scaling is needed.
<br />
<br />Since the large sprites are composed of many smaller ones, if you slowly move all the sprites towards the center of the character it will look like it's shrinking.
<br />
<br />They seem to have used that method for the SNES sprite in that thread, and I believe this was done on <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d5GaIupGEBc" class="postlink">Yuu Yuu Hakusho - Makyou Toitsusen</a> on the MD. When the players jump to the background plane (C + UP) they shrink a bit.
<br />
<br />It seems it's possible to do some shrinking this way before the sprites get terribly distorted. Also, I imagine tha the smaller the sprites you use to compose the character the better this technique will work (i.e. 8x8 will look better than 32x32).
<br />
<br />Maybe combining this with Mode 7 background scaling will look pretty decent.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
